description: Feel Like A Stranger-> They Love Each Other, Little Red Rooster, Dire Wolf, Cassidy, Big Railroad Blues, The Music Never Stopped-> Don't Ease Me In Cryptical Envelopement-> The Other One-> Eyes Of The World-> Don't Need Love-> Drums-> Nobody's Fault But Mine-> Truckin'-> Smokestack Lightning-> Comes A Time-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: It's All Over Now Baby Blue

reviews.review_text:
hot This is a great sounding SBD.  The sound is crystal clear, and the show is great.

Here's some cover-art for this show:
http://www.toddalbert.com/music/cover_art/

Good Times, Good Times Great show. Lots of energy and a hot recording. The last Cryptical, I think -- if not, it's definately the last of the '85 resurrection. 

If you're reassembling the show or touching it up for your own archives, the tape flip at TMNS>Don't Ease is virtually seamless, and both tracks need to have their channels swapped. The cut in Space->Nobody's Fault is not as pretty, though.

1985 Rules!! Typical first set for this year.  The second set is the complete opposite!!  It absolutely smokes.  I have read people saying that the (6/16 Greek) Cryptical > Other 1 > Cryptical is the best but I beg to differ!  This Starlight version (that opens up the second set!!) is the tightest and hottest.  Nice Eyes and Nobody's Fault as well.  Comes A Time is always a treat.  Can't say enough cool things about 1985!!
This Cryptical > Other 1 > Cryptical Rules! GDTrey is correct, this is the most intense and well played versions of the above in 85.  Crank it up.

Setlists do not tell all This is a good show for this leg of the tour from '85 but GOOD GRIEF Jerry's voice is wasted on the Cryptical.  Sorry to say but it's TERRIBLE.  The Eyes goes a mile a minute and passes by too quickly.  Bad freebase.  Bad.  Bad.  Good set list, mediocre performance.  

BTW, the best Cryptical > Other One > Cryptical happened sometime in 1969.  That was probably implied by previous posts but just wanted to make that clear.  Nice idea with the Cryptical breakout at the Greek, but it's a good thing there were no more Crypticals played after this show so that it wasn't dragged through the mud further.  Look to the summer for better '85 shows.

1st set I agree with the reviewer before me. I'm not big on the 2nd set. Although the song selection is great, Jerry's voice just isn't up to par.  The 1st set on the other hand is a gem. If you're as obsessive as me you'll download the whole show but that 1st set is CLASSIC '85.  Get it for that.
stars and stripes solid, sears and roebuck '85.  the entire backdrop was one huge american flag.  labor day in the u.s.a.!!!  mighty fine.

dont be so damn picky i like jerrys voice no matter how it sounds, its not even that bad really,fuck man how would anybody listen to bob dylan if ur gonna be that picky, and truthfully he still sounds better than phil ever did   this soundboard is good a little shaky at times but im only bein a little negative cuss theres alot of great 85 soundboards

All jazzed-up We drove from Racine Wisconsin and where the first people to arrive at the Starlight theater parkinglot. We met a law student from Stanford who had a nice car audio system and we had the Frost 82 tapes playing through it mid afternoon, he gave us a Lewiston 80 tape. I was blue Gelled as well. Parking lot scene was super mellow and some folks where giving out hugs before the show.It was a clear blue sky day Bobby came out with a purple t-shirt that seemed too big for him,We had 8th row on jer's side. The 'Eyes' was incredible. There's a small lake there surrounded by trees and rocky cliffs that we found to hang out and we met some heads who lost there shoes and needed ours to buy food in a store. It was a few hours before show time and a peace loving hippy walked towards our car and I asked him what time is was..he said 'Who Cares'his words came on like a roaring semi on a highway..we where way out there........This show is probably the most unique of 1985.barely a 4 for quality but almost a five for playing. The Other One,Space,Stranger,Theylove and Eyes are amazing..and Cryptical is here too

purple gel cool late summer swing from oklahoma to kc to the rocks. have to admit it's easy to have this superb venue impact the review. i was in the pit and although i agree cryptical was way ragged, the other one out of it positively floored me and i've yet to recover. nobody's fault but mine revived an old tune the dead had visited back in the early 70's maybe. the purple gels were real fine and somehow i made it to morrison. anyway,the show was just ok but if you were actually there you probably recall this affair fondly.

All about the Love A competent 80's show. Nothing awful and a few moments of magic. Soundboard sounds fine.  Bobby lovelight rap reminds how incredible Pig was. Brent don't need love anymore so Jerry points out there comes a time followed by the Lovelight. Maybe they were trying to tell Brent something. A sweet Baby Blue for those not going on to the Rocks and points West.

4 STARS for Heart I am giving this show 4 stars for an amazing setlist and the heart that is displayed throughout the show.
It may not have have been the best show in town musically, but 'Cryptical', I only wish I could have seen a JERRY Cryptical.
'Dire Wolf' is 5 stars, and 'Comes a Time' is always a treat.

I wish it were still goin' on today.

cryptical the thing that stands out about this show was the venue, small personable and unigue in its features that it looked like a castle with a mote and two towers on each side .. Never mind that they played crip other one crip but the place was on fire with purple jelliebellies and moist of the heads jumped the fence!!!!!!!!!!!

Storyline I was convinced at the time that when Brent and Bobby did 'Don't Need You', that they were directing their ire at Garcia who had left the stage rather abruptly right in the middle of the Eyes jam. 
When Garcia came ot after drums and broke into "Nobody's Fault But Mine", I was sure that he was in fact apologizing.

What might have been Haven't heard this one for a long time, dusted it off tonight.
Starts with a nice stranger, Garcia is hot, bands tight, then goes dud for TLEO and Rooster (Sorry, just don't care for the tunes).Then comes Dire Wolf and we are off on one of the early 80's space cowboy sets. Garcia rages through wolf, takes it right on into Cassidy where he is on fire. Merge into Big RR and the band is kicking on all gears, just flat out stomping. Garcia is one hot ass guitarist and is picking with that extra honky-tonk pizzaz, smoking the song right into Music, which is speedy but delightful. Finish of TLEO and it's a pretty fair set by the standards of the day.
Come out 2nd set, stars are emerging as night falls and whatever the Boys did backstage hasn't stopped em at all because they are just beast- a ravenous machine that smashes through TOO, Bobby howling the final verses, the band all falling chaos and glowing strokes. Roll right into a very nice eyes, Garcia is noodling like the old days, everything is wonderful and it looks like one of the shows of the year...and then Huh? Drummers kick in hard in eyes, sound like we are moving straight into drumz/space, but the band wanders on for a bit, Brent does his thing, Drumz /space and then the band just freaking mails it in from here on out.
This is a what could have been show. It had the ability to be great, the band was at the top of their game, and just went sideways in the 2nd set.
Amazing show! Get the Oade Brothers Schoeps recording, nothing better.
